Former Manchester United midfielder, Paul Scholes and former defender, Gary Neville, have declared the club ‘circus’ open for business again amid the uncertainty surrounding Cristiano Ronaldo’s future. Scholes wants the issues with the 37-year-old treated as quickly as possible to enable the club move on. Ronaldo returned to Manchester United last summer amid almost unprecedented hype and fanfare, following his decision to quit Juventus. The club appointed former Ajax boss, Erik ten Hag to take over and change things for the better at Old Trafford but his summer rebuild has got off to a slow start. Ronaldo, however, is said to be frustrated at the lack of progress United have made in the transfer window and has declared his intention to dump the club He wrote on Instagram: “Let the circus begin.” Scholes’ former teammate Gary Neville, meanwhile, echoed those sentiments and urged United’s key decision-makers to come to a swift and decisive conclusion. He wrote on Twitter: “The only important factor with the Ronaldo situation is that it’s dealt with decisively and quickly. “This can’t be a saga that takes the focus away from ETH bedding in period for the next two months.”